; co-learning-stream.fk — the LIVE per-device learning loop as a FOLD, then the federated speedup over streams.
;
; co-learning.fk (M0) proved the federated UNION over exemplar sets that were handed to it already-learned;
; learning-arc.fk folded ONE device's stream and measured its own online agreement curve. This brick is the
; piece between them — co-learning M1: each device GROWS its exemplar set by folding its OWN oracle stream,
; and THEN the merged breadth of two devices' learned sets beats either alone. The whole "two mics learn
; faster together" claim, now from STREAMS rather than from pre-handed sets.
;
; A device's audio arrives as a stream of SAMPLES, each (list label feature) — the oracle's label (speech,
; music, ...) and the coarse feature-vector that was sensed (small-int bins, nearest-shape's query shape).
; LEARNING is the smallest act (nearest-shape.fk / learning-arc.fk): intern one exemplar. The exemplar IS
; nearest-shape's prototype shape (list label vector) — so (cons (list label feature) set) grows the set and
; the next query can route to it. cls-learn-stream FOLDS the whole stream into the device's set; the fold is
; online, single-pass, order-respecting — replay the stream, get the identical set on Go, Rust, and TS.
;
; THE FEDERATED SPEEDUP OVER STREAMS: device A's stream teaches {speech}, device B's teaches {music}. After
; each folds its own stream, A's set recognizes only speech (a music query routes wrong — partial), B's only
; music. cls-merged-breadth folds BOTH streams and unions the learned sets (cl-merge); the union recognizes
; BOTH, and its breadth is the sum of what each mic alone could cover. Two streams cover what one cannot.
;
; A sample  = (list label feature-vector). A stream = a list of samples, in time order.
; A device's learned set = a list of (label vector) — exactly nearest-shape's prototype-set.
;
; Composes: nearest-shape.fk (ns-label, via cl-knows?) + co-learning.fk (cl-merge, cl-breadth, cl-knows?).
; Proven by: form-stdlib/tests/co-learning-stream-band.fk (four-way at validate.sh, incl. fkwu).

(do
    ; --- a sample's parts: the oracle's label, and the feature the mic sensed. ---
    (defn cls-label   (sample) (nth sample 0))   ; "speech" / "music" / ...
    (defn cls-feature (sample) (nth sample 1))   ; the coarse feature-vector (nearest-shape query shape)

    ; --- LEARN one sample: intern it as nearest-shape's (label vector) prototype, growing the set. ---
    ; the exemplar prepends; every prior exemplar remains (adding without forgetting).
    (defn cls-learn (sample set) (cons (list (cls-label sample) (cls-feature sample)) set))

    ; --- THE LIVE LOOP AS A FOLD: walk the stream in time order, interning each sample into the set. ---
    ; (samples set) — fold the remaining stream onto the set learned so far; base case returns the set.
    ; cold (empty stream) → the set unchanged: a device that heard nothing learned nothing.
    (defn cls-learn-stream (samples set)
        (if (eq (len samples) 0) set
            (cls-learn-stream (tail samples) (cls-learn (head samples) set))))

    ; --- A DEVICE learns from scratch: fold its whole stream onto the empty set. ---
    (defn cls-device (samples) (cls-learn-stream samples (empty)))

    ; --- THE FEDERATED SPEEDUP: breadth of the UNION of two devices' learned sets (cl-merge over the
    ;     two folded streams). The merged field covers what each mic alone could not — and its breadth
    ;     is the measure of that coverage. cl-breadth/cl-merge are co-learning.fk's. ---
    (defn cls-merged-breadth (stream-a stream-b)
        (cl-breadth (cl-merge (cls-device stream-a) (cls-device stream-b))))

    ; --- does a device that folded `samples` recognize `query` as `label`? (cl-knows? over the learned
    ;     set — nearest-shape under the hood). The handle the band uses to show A-alone is PARTIAL. ---
    (defn cls-stream-knows? (samples query label) (cl-knows? query (cls-device samples) label))
    0)